[White "Short & Sweet"]
[Black "Open Sicilian - 6. Bg5 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "40"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 {Controlling the central e5-square and preparing Nf6!} 3. d4
{Going for the Open Sicilian.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {Developing the knight, made
possible by our pawn on d6.} 5. Nc3 a6 {This move defines the Najdorf. Now we
want to push e5 and Bb5+ is no longer an issue.} 6. Bg5 e6 {One reason I chose
the 3-piece system over others @@StartBracket@@for example over Gelfand
variation with 7...Nbd7 without 7...Be7@@EndBracket@@ is the fact that there
are relatively few sidelines for White that are dangerous for us. That said,
it is important to know how to deal with them and you may actually encounter
them if you are facing less experienced players, although, what am I saying, I
have personally faced one against Magnus Carlsen himself...} 7. f4 Be7 8. Qf3
Qc7 {The right move order, as 8...Nbd7 first allows 9.Bc4 , which can be very
unpleasant here.} 9. f5 {With the knight not yet on d7, Black can't play 9...
e5 as it runs into 10.Bxf6 followed by Nd5 and so this move is not so easy to
meet. As a rule, in the Sicilian structures, if the knight is still on b8, the
f5 push is usually well met with Nc6, trading the d4 knight and thus relieving
some of the pressure on the potentially soft e6 point.} Nc6 {I had thoroughly
investigated both this option and also including 9...h6 10.Bh4 and only then
10...Nc6 I have finally concluded that this one is simpler. Basically, there
is no need to create a potential hook for White's g4-g5 push.} 10. Nxc6 {This
has never been played, but it seems more testing.} bxc6 11. g4 d5 {A strike in
the center, but also very importantly, opening the e7 bishop to contribute to
the potential play on the queenside.} 12. O-O-O Rb8 {The b-file just has to be
taken. Now Black gets ideas of his own with Qb6 or Qa5 and some tricks like
Ba3 or even Rxb2 potentially. Potentially.} 13. Bf4 {This is a challenging
move.} e5 14. Bg3 O-O {Closing the position with 14...d4 is also possible, but
keeping the tension in the center gives Black more obvious counterplay against
White's obvious idea of the g4-g5 push.} 15. h4 dxe4 {A direct way to release
the tension and start forcing matters.} 16. Nxe4 Qa5 {Introducing all sorts of
ideas on the queenside, for now, Qxa2.} 17. Bc4 Nxe4 18. Qxe4 Rxb2 {The point
of our play. Taking the rook loses.} 19. Kxb2 Ba3+ 20. Kb1 Qb4+ {Winning the
queen.} *

