1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 {Controlling the central e5-square and preparing Nf6!} 3. d4
{Going for the Open Sicilian.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {Developing the knight, made
possible by our pawn on d6.} 5. Nc3 a6 {This move defines the Najdorf. Now we
want to push e5 and Bb5+ is no longer an issue.} 6. Bg5 e6 {One reason I chose
the 3-piece system over others @@StartBracket@@for example over Gelfand
variation with 7...Nbd7 without 7...Be7@@EndBracket@@ is the fact that there
are relatively few sidelines for White that are dangerous for us. That said,
it is important to know how to deal with them and you may actually encounter
them if you are facing less experienced players, although, what am I saying, I
have personally faced one against Magnus Carlsen himself...} 7. f4 Be7 8. Qf3
Qc7 {The right move order, as 8...Nbd7 first allows 9.Bc4 , which can be very
unpleasant here.} 9. O-O-O {Starting with 9.Bd3 will most likely transpose and
the only sensible alternative to the long castle is the 9.f5!? push.} Nbd7 {
The main-line 10. g4 will be analyzed later, here I would like to take a look
at the main alternative 10. Bd3.} 10. Bd3 {From a theoretical viewpoint the
move 10.g4 is a lot more critical, but this move does require quite a bit of
knowledge and accuracy from the Black players. Fortunately, you've got this
course, so let's study it.} b5 {This has to be our main-line. It allows some
sacrifices, but the positional 10...h6 doesn't quite equalize against the best
play, I believe.} 11. Rhe1 {White is mobilizing his pieces and prepares for an
eventual shot in the center with e5 or Nd5.} Bb7 12. Nd5 {Is actually a legit
sacrifice.} exd5 13. Nf5 Kf8 14. exd5 Bd8 15. Qg3 Rg8 {Defending against the
Bh6 idea.} 16. Nxg7 Rxg7 17. Bh6 Nh5 18. Qe3 {White has enough compensation
for the sacrificed material here.} Ndf6 {Black has many ways to play here, but
this is the easiest way to simplify the position somewhat. For example, 19.g4
Qc5 Forcing a queen trade. 20.Qxc5 dxc5 21.gxh5 Ng8 22.Bxg7+ Kxg7 23.d6 Nf6
The d-pawn is far, but should never actually queen with Black having firm
control over the d8 square. Black is totally fine.} *

