1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 {Controlling the central e5-square and preparing Nf6!} 3. d4
{Going for the Open Sicilian.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {Developing the knight, made
possible by our pawn on d6.} 5. Nc3 a6 {This move defines the Najdorf. Now we
want to push e5 and Bb5+ is no longer an issue.} 6. Bg5 e6 {One reason I chose
the 3-piece system over others @@StartBracket@@for example over Gelfand
variation with 7...Nbd7 without 7...Be7@@EndBracket@@ is the fact that there
are relatively few sidelines for White that are dangerous for us. That said,
it is important to know how to deal with them and you may actually encounter
them if you are facing less experienced players, although, what am I saying, I
have personally faced one against Magnus Carlsen himself...} 7. f4 Be7 8. Qf3
Qc7 {The right move order, as 8...Nbd7 first allows 9.Bc4 , which can be very
unpleasant here.} 9. O-O-O {Starting with 9.Bd3 will most likely transpose and
the only sensible alternative to the long castle is the 9.f5!? push.} Nbd7 {
We've arrived at the main-line:} 10. g4 {The main and the most principled move.
Most of your well-prepared opponents who go for 6.Bg5 will blitz all of their
moves including this one!} h6 {In preparation for this course, while I was
going to re-examine the main-line starting with 10...b5 I had by accident
stumbled upon this old forgotten line and discovered, to my surprise, that it
is perfectly correct and sound. As I was running the strongest hardware, it
became quite quickly obvious that it is very fine for Black, but I did check
it very thoroughly nonetheless and my first impression was confirmed. I am
sure this line will gain a lot of followers both, over the board and
correspondence chess and what is very important for the modern player is that
it is a lot more suited for faster online chess, as Black's play is a lot more
intuitive here, compared to the crazy move-by-move engine lines that one has
to remember in the Poisoned Pawn variation. Just in case, I will also give the
highly reliable 10...b5 line, in the next chapter, to make sure the students
of my course have some options and are not an immovable target for the well
prepared 6.Bg5 aficionados, once the surprise effect of 10...h6 drops.} 11. Qh3
{Turned out to be a very serious test here as well. It is barely played here.}
Nc5 12. Bg2 {Developing the bishop while also protecting e4, by far the most
critical move here.} Rg8 {Always a move to keep in mind, moving out of the pin
and forcing White to take a decision after all.} 13. Bxf6 Bxf6 {Black has a
strong bishop here and White has to act fast if he wants to use his temporary
lead in development.} 14. b4 {A very concrete idea.} Nd7 15. g5 {A very
forceful concrete sequence.} hxg5 16. e5 {Now actually 16...dxe5 would lose to
17.Nxe6 but having collected one pawn already, and with White having weakened
the long diagonal with b2-b4, we can sacrifice a piece @@StartBracket@@or
rather trade a piece for three pawns@@EndBracket@@, without too many doubts.}
Nxe5 17. fxe5 Bxe5 {Black has a fine position with a super-strong bishop and a
bunch of pawns. White's best bet is probably to sac an exchange for that
monster on e5.} 18. Rhe1 Bd7 19. Rxe5 dxe5 20. Nb3 {And with Na5-Nc5 White has
some play, but Black is doing perfectly fine after} Rd8 {Intending Bc8, with a
strange material balance, which is quite balanced, but intended.} *

