1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 {Controlling the central e5-square and preparing Nf6!} 3. d4
{Going for the Open Sicilian.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {Developing the knight, made
possible by our pawn on d6.} 5. Nc3 a6 {This move defines the Najdorf. Now we
want to push e5 and Bb5+ is no longer an issue.} 6. Be3 e5 7. Nf3 Be7 {Here
traditionally the main move has been 8.Bc4 fighting for the d5 square, but
there are two interesting trendy alternatives 8.Nd2!? and the very fresh 8.h3}
8. Nd2 {The idea is simple, Black wants to reroute the knight via c4-b6 to d5.
A noble idea, but he does make many moves with the same piece.} b5 {Often this
move can be premature if played before castling and any other development of
the queenside, but here it is justified with the fact that White moved one of
his knights far too many times and blocked the view of the d1 queen.} 9. a4 {
This is White's standard response, whenever Black plays b5 this early on.} b4 {
The obvious reply, there is no other good way of dealing with the b5 pawn
hanging, as bxa4 allows Nc4-Nb6.} 10. Nd5 Nxd5 11. exd5 {The knight find quite
some use on c4, the only problem now is that it takes White too much time and
his f1 bishop is still there undeveloped.} O-O 12. Nc4 {The knight find quite
some use on c4, the only problem now is that it takes White too much time and
his f1 bishop is still there undeveloped.} Nd7 13. a5 f5 {I had a game here
myself with the Black pieces against Wei Yi and I mixed something up and
played Rb8 first. I then went on to play a poor game, but in the end, was
lucky to hold it. Of course Black has to play fast dynamic chess and f5! is
the right way to go. Let's look at few options.} 14. f3 {This has been played
a few times, but it seems really provocative to me and I am glad my engines
came up with a rough response.} f4 {One of the ways to open up the position,
using White's lag in the development of his kingside.} 15. Bf2 Bh4 16. g3 e4 {
Dynamic chess at its best.} 17. fxe4 Bg5 {Black has excellent compensation
here, with all the following moves going forward.} 18. Bd3 Qf6 19. O-O Ne5 {
With a complex position, typical for Najdorf where Black is certainly having
fun. There have surely also been alternatives on the way.} *

[Event "?"]
