[PlyCount "36"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 {Controlling the central e5-square and preparing Nf6!} 3. d4
{Going for the Open Sicilian.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {Developing the knight, made
possible by our pawn on d6.} 5. Nc3 a6 {This move defines the Najdorf. Now we
want to push e5 and Bb5+ is no longer an issue.} 6. Be3 e5 7. Nb3 Be7 8. f3 {
This chapter is dedicated to the English Attack, one of White's most popular
setups against the Najdorf.} Be6 9. Qd2 h5 {A trendy and a fresh system, that
I am happy to be recommending here. I played it myself a few times already,
but also many other top players did, most notably it was the choice of Magnus
Carlsen himself, who adopted it after encountering it against Ding Liren. Now
White is mostly choosing between three different setups 10.O-O-O , 10.Be2 and
10.Nd5} 10. Nd5 {My main recommendation is 10...Nxd5 , but in the Short &
Sweet, I will show you my alternative solution:} Bxd5 {I don't think this is
one hundred percent correct but definitely worth having it in our arsenal of
possibilities.} 11. exd5 Nbd7 12. O-O-O {The most critical.} Qc7 {The move I
played against Levon. 12...Rc8 also can be investigated, but I had a
particular idea here after 12...Qc7 .} 13. c4 {This is a very counterintuitive
move, playing from the king, before even moving it across, but the idea is to
be able to meet Nb6 with Qa5! and not lose the d5 pawn in the process.} a5 14.
Kb1 {Now there are a couple of games with a4-a3 push, but after 14...a4 White
has a strong move 15.Nc1! with a strong idea of Ne2 @@StartBracket@@ or a3
followed by Na2!@@EndBracket@@ Nc3-Nb5. My new idea is to inverse the move
order and set up a very beautiful positional exchange sac.} O-O 15. Na1 a4 16.
Nc2 {The most natural response, White plans to go Na3-Nb5 what could be wrong?}
a3 {What?!} 17. Nxa3 {Of course, it is possible to play 17.b3 here as well,
but the knight on c2 will be very misplaced then, too far away from the ideal
c3/b5 squares. Black will then push for b5 plans after some preliminary
regrouping like Rfc8 Nc5 Qd7 Bd8.} Rxa3 {Boom!} 18. bxa3 Ra8 {Isn't this
beautiful. With the b-pawn gone from the b-file, the c5 square is eternally
under Black's control. White's king is wide open, Black has potential access
to the long diagonal and some open and semi-open files on the queenside. I
think definitely worth a shot, despite the greedy computer being able to
defend this and claim some objective advantage for White.} *

