1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 {Controlling the central e5-square and preparing Nf6!} 3. d4
{Going for the Open Sicilian.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {Developing the knight, made
possible by our pawn on d6.} 5. Nc3 a6 {This move defines the Najdorf. Now we
want to push e5 and Bb5+ is no longer an issue.} 6. h3 {One of the most
principled lines, which by now no longer looks as strange as it looked at
first. White basically wants to prepare the g2-g4 push.} e5 {By no means the
only playable system, but in my course, I had chosen to, whenever possible,
recommend the Fischer-style 6...e5 structure. The Scheveningen structures with
6...e6 are particularly interesting here, now that White has spent a move on
h2-h3, which is often a waste of time when White later pushes g4-g5 and h3-h4
anyway. Also possible are the Dragon setups with 6...g6 and there are even
some rare alternatives, like the direct 6...h6!? tried by Magnus Carlsen
himself, albeit in a blitz game.} 7. Nb3 {The other main-move 7.Nde2 will be
examined in the next variation.} Be7 8. g4 h6 {This slows down White's
kingside play tremendously and it should be played.} 9. Be3 b5 {This idea is
connected with a cool exchange sacrifice after 10.Nd5 Bb7!? There are also
alternatives, such as 10...Be6 or the more cunning 10...Nbd7 !?} 10. Nd5 {The
most principled move.} Bb7 {A brilliant exchange sacrifice. Quite incredible
that it actually works.} 11. Bb6 {Obviously the critical move. If White
doesn't take up the challenge, Black shouldn't be too worried.} Qc8 12. Nc7+
Kf8 13. Nxa8 {Here Black gets to pick up the e4 pawn with a tempo as well.}
Bxe4 14. Rg1 Bxa8 {With good play. Black has a strong central pawn for the
exchange and a lot of easy moves will come with tempi, thanks to the awkward
b6 bishop. Eventually, Black's king will settle on g7.} *

