1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 {Controlling the central e5-square and preparing Nf6!} 3. d4
{Going for the Open Sicilian.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {Developing the knight, made
possible by our pawn on d6.} 5. Nc3 a6 {This move defines the Najdorf. Now we
want to push e5 and Bb5+ is no longer an issue.} 6. h3 {One of the most
principled lines, which by now no longer looks as strange as it looked at
first. White basically wants to prepare the g2-g4 push.} e5 {By no means the
only playable system, but in my course, I had chosen to, whenever possible,
recommend the Fischer-style 6...e5 structure. The Scheveningen structures with
6...e6 are particularly interesting here, now that White has spent a move on
h2-h3, which is often a waste of time when White later pushes g4-g5 and h3-h4
anyway. Also possible are the Dragon setups with 6...g6 and there are even
some rare alternatives, like the direct 6...h6!? tried by Magnus Carlsen
himself, albeit in a blitz game.} 7. Nde2 {The most popular move and a logical
one too, White wants to push the pawn to g4 and then relocate the knight to g3.
} h5 {By far the main move and understandably so. Stopping g2-g4 is a huge
deal, not just to stop g4 in itself, but much more important not to allow
White to employ the e2 knight harmoniously to g3. Previously there have been
just two theoretical moves here, 8.g3 and 8.Bg5 but by now more moves started
popping up here.} 8. g3 {This used to be one of the main tabias at the high
level and it is still regularly played. I have also come across this line a
lot in my online games- I think it is quite popular at various levels. Here
Black has an abundance of options. There is of course the usual development
scheme with Be7 Be6 Nbd7, when White goes a2-a4 at some point, and getting
b7-b5 push will be a challenge. There are also lines where Black pushes b5
early on, either now immediately or after first playing Be6 or Be7, both of
which I had employed myself. Finally, there is a setup with Nbd7 first, with
or without including Be7 Bg2, when White usually responds with a4 stopping b5,
and then Black has to develop the c8 bishop with a more modest- b7-b6 move. I
think pretty much all of these systems are very playable, but I will go with 8.
..Be7 9.Bg2 b5 setup, something I have played myself in the last tournament
game I had so far here, against Nepo.} Be7 9. Bg2 b5 {The good thing about
systems with b5 is that at least we got b5 in, already.} 10. Nd5 {This is the
cultured move, otherwise Black will have a very comfortable game, having
pushed b5 already and with White still not solving his issues of the e2 knight.
} Nxd5 {The other line 10...Nbd7 is also very serious, but I chose this one.}
11. Qxd5 {Black loses some time on the awkward move} Ra7 {but White's queen on
d5 is misplaced and he will have to spend a couple of tempi to regroup.} 12.
Be3 {There are alternatives, but this move is by far the most natural,
developing the bishop with a tempo.} Rb7 {This is a very smart move. It is a
lot more tempting to play Be6 with a tempo and then choose Rb7 or Rd7, but the
point is, White most likely wants to drop the queen back anyway, while for
Black it is better to keep the flexibility, as he often wants to develop
Nd7-Nf6 first and keep the bishop on c8 for the time being. White's most
obvious idea here is to regroup with Qd2 Nc3-Nd5, but there are also other
ways to play, such as castling long and trying to push the kingside pawns,
which is a lot riskier.} 13. Qd2 {There are a lot of transpositions here, but
most of the games featured one of the two obvious plans, either to castle long
or to go for O-O Qd2 Nc3 setup in some order or the other.} Nd7 14. O-O-O {
Castling long here is not very promising for White.} b4 {Taking away the c3
square from the knight and grabbing some space is even more logical here, now
that White had castled straight into this.} 15. f4 a5 16. g4 {White is also
trying to create some play and advance his pawns.} h4 {Keeping the kingside
shut and very importantly taking away the g3 square from the knight. Note how
the e2 knight is being neutralized by our e5, b4, and h4 pawns.} 17. g5 {White
keeps pushing, though there is no clear threat.} Rc7 {This is a strong move,
typical for this line. The rook moves to the side and place itself onto the
semi-open file, and allows the c8 bishop to develop itself on b7.} 18. Kb1 Bb7
{Black has an easy play here, targetting the e4 pawn, while White's kingside
advance hasn't yielded him anything concrete.} *

