1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 {Controlling the central e5-square and preparing Nf6!} 3. d4
{Going for the Open Sicilian.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {Developing the knight, made
possible by our pawn on d6.} 5. Nc3 a6 {This move defines the Najdorf. Now we
want to push e5 and Bb5+ is no longer an issue.} 6. Be2 {This modest system
throughout the times has remained one of the most commonly played systems on
all levels. White is focussing on the kingside development, wants to modestly
develop his f1 bishop, get the king out of the center, and see how to proceed
later. Here there are @@StartBracket@@as so often!@@EndBracket@@ two
conceptually different ways to play with Black, but those who have been
through the previous chapters already know that I will recommend the
Fischer-style 6...e5 push as opposed to the 6...e6 Scheveningen setup. The
Scheveningen setup is very playable here, obviously, but beware, if you want
to play it, you not only have to deal with 7.O-O but also with plans involving
the long castle after 7.Be3} e5 {Here White has almost exclusively played 7.
Nb3 at the highest level and 7.Nf3 was considered a rookie mistake until it
has been reintroduced to the highest level a few years ago by Magnus Carlsen
and it caught in popularity. The thing is, the knight seemed to be blocking
the f2 pawn, but in fact in the position after 7.Nf3 Be7 8.Bg5 Be6 9.Bxf6 Bxf6
the knight stands at the very least as well on f3 as it does on b3. And
although from the stats I had done, at the club and amateur level I would
still expect you to face 7.Nb3 almost ten times more often than 7.Nf3 , I
think it is important to know what we are aiming for here as well.} 7. Nf3 Be7
{The alternative 7...h6 can be investigated, but 7...Be6 is no longer an
option here, as it can be hit by 8.Ng5! which is one of the advantages of 7.
Nf3 over 7.Nb3.} 8. Bg5 {The point of this entire 7.Nf3 line. Of course, White
can just develop here in some other way, but then Black gets a very
comfortable position. I will not cover all possible moves, there are too many
and none of them are too challenging, but I will give one instructive line.}
Be6 {The alternative is 8...Nbd7 which I would only recommend you playing once
you study the subtleties very well because the risk is high that White will
tie you down there and get the dominant control over the d5 square. The
position after 8...Be6 is a lot simpler to grasp; currently, we want to
reinforce the f6 knight with Nbd7, so White pretty much has to take.} 9. Bxf6
Bxf6 {Here, White usually makes one of the three moves: 10.Nd5 , 10.O-O , and
10.Qd2 , but basically, there are two setups that White has employed so far.
One is O-O with Qd2 and the other is O-O with Nd5 and Bc4. There are a few
move order subtleties though.} 10. O-O O-O {Here White again has a few options.
11.Nd5 and 11.Qd2 are common and I would also like to mention 11.a4 which is
an interesting alternative as well.} 11. Nd5 Nd7 {Taking on d5 is not
something we want to do here, as that would lead to a position tempo down for
us, compared to the one we reach after @@StartFEN@@rn1q1rk1/1p3ppp/p2pbb2/4p3/
4P3/2N2N2/PPP1BPPP/R2Q1RK1 w - - 2 11@@EndFEN@@ 11.Qd2} 12. Bc4 {White
reinforces control over the d5 square. In case of any other move we could play
Rc8 and the bishop on e2 would have no purpose.} Qc8 {Black has a bunch of
different options and ideas here. The most common way of playing is also what
I had played and faced @@StartBracket@@with Black against Vishy Anand and
White against Duda!@@EndBracket@@ 12...Rc8 13.Qe2 Nb6 simplifying the position
into a knight vs bishop position, similar to one we will study in 6.a4 chapter.
Here, however, I propose this elegant regroup, which is a novelty as of now.
The idea is to free the d8 square for the bishop.} 13. Qe2 {The most natural
reply. Simply taking on f6 and e6 leads to a comfortable position for us, as
we will have fine control over the d5 square.} b5 14. Bb3 Bd8 {The bishop is
hoping for a better future on some other diagonals, but for now, the main
purpose of this is to get out of the Nxf6+, prepare Nc5, and eventually push
f7-f5.} 15. a3 Nc5 {It comes in handy that the d8 bishop is guarding the b6
square.} 16. Ba2 Kh8 {Making the intentions clear. Next up is the f5 push.} 17.
Rad1 f5 {This gives Black excellent play on the kingside.} 18. exf5 Bxf5 {Now
Bg4 is a direct threat.} 19. Ne3 Bg6 {We will not let White in peace. The
threat of a pin is resumed.} 20. Rxd6 Bh5 {Threatening e4 when White is
already on the defensive.} *

