1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 {Controlling the central e5-square and preparing Nf6!} 3. d4
{Going for the Open Sicilian.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {Developing the knight, made
possible by our pawn on d6.} 5. Nc3 a6 {This move defines the Najdorf. Now we
want to push e5 and Bb5+ is no longer an issue.} 6. Be2 {This modest system
throughout the times has remained one of the most commonly played systems on
all levels. White is focussing on the kingside development, wants to modestly
develop his f1 bishop, get the king out of the center, and see how to proceed
later. Here there are @@StartBracket@@as so often!@@EndBracket@@ two
conceptually different ways to play with Black, but those who have been
through the previous chapters already know that I will recommend the
Fischer-style 6...e5 push as opposed to the 6...e6 Scheveningen setup. The
Scheveningen setup is very playable here, obviously, but beware, if you want
to play it, you not only have to deal with 7.O-O but also with plans involving
the long castle after 7.Be3} e5 {Here White has almost exclusively played 7.
Nb3 at the highest level and 7.Nf3 was considered a rookie mistake until it
has been reintroduced to the highest level a few years ago by Magnus Carlsen
and it caught in popularity. The thing is, the knight seemed to be blocking
the f2 pawn, but in fact in the position after 7.Nf3 Be7 8.Bg5 Be6 9.Bxf6 Bxf6
the knight stands at the very least as well on f3 as it does on b3. And
although from the stats I had done, at the club and amateur level I would
still expect you to face 7.Nb3 almost ten times more often than 7.Nf3 , I
think it is important to know what we are aiming for here as well.} 7. Nb3 Be7
{This is the traditional and 'approved' move order here. Black is not rushing
with Be6, not to get under a quick f4-f5.} 8. O-O O-O {The traditional move
order, once again. Here 8...Be6 first is possible, trying to outsmart White,
especially if he wants to play the modern Qd3 Nd5 system. We will examine that
in the6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 Be6 chapter, The old wisdom is that Black should not rush
with Be6, not to fall into the f2-f4 push, which is why the waiting move 9.
Kh1!? is quite popular in this position; even there White is hoping for Black
to go 9...Be6 and then get 10.f4! and recapture on f4 in one go, having Kh1 as
a useful extra tempo, compared to the @@StartFEN@@rnbq1rk1/1p2bppp/p2p1n2/4p3/
4P3/1NN5/PPP1BPPP/R1BQ1RK1 w - - 4 9@@EndFEN@@ 9.Be3 Be6 10.f4 exf4 11.Bxf4
variation.} 9. Be3 {The main theoretical move here. Actually, this used to be
the main-line in connection with a4 Qd2 setup, but now it is the main-line in
connection with the Qd3 Nd5 idea. Fun fact.} Be6 10. Qd3 {This line is highly
debated for the past few years on the top-level.} Nbd7 11. Nd5 Bxd5 {Now that
the knight is on d7 and the bishop can't retreat to c8, Black takes with the
bishop and not the knight.} 12. exd5 h5 {There is an ocean of correspondence
games here and a bunch of high-level games. Most of the games are connected
with the Ne8 f5 plan in one order or the other, there are also, few other,
subtle setups, that have been tested, but I wanted to recommend something very
fresh for this course and offer this wicked idea that has so far been only
played once, by an Indian theoretician, long time second to Vishy Anand and
later Harikrishna, Surya Shekhar Ganguly. For starters, the idea is to throw
the knight to g4 and then push the f-pawn or trade the bishops with Bg5, much
like after the main-move 12...Ne8 If White prevents this with h3, then we will
play the position traditionally with the g6 Ne8
@@StartBracket@@Nh7!?@@EndBracket@@ plan and the inclusion of the moves h5 and
h3 on the kingside is likely to benefit us, as we are the ones attacking this
side of the board.} 13. a4 {Quite critical, White is pushing his a-pawn to a5
first, before pushing c4 and ignores our Ng4 idea. The idea is that if we now
play a6-a5, our b5 square will be quite weak and White's e2 bishop will have
access to it, unlike the 13.c4 a5 position. Also with the pawn not being on c4,
the c5 square is less of an outpost, as in the long run there can be the c3-b4
push.} Ng4 {We proceed with our idea, though it is also possible to start with
13...g6 and jump with the knight on the next move.} 14. Bd2 f5 {Using the fact
that the White queen has no attractive squares available after 15.h3 e4!} 15.
h3 e4 {The point. White doesn't have a good square for the queen; wherever he
goes he will get hit.} 16. Qc4 {Is also not a good idea, as it allows the
knight to retreat with a tempo.} Nge5 {Hitting the queen and next we want to
continue our play on the kingside.} 17. Qb4 a5 {Inviting the knight to a5, to
get the f4 push by tactical means.} 18. Nxa5 f4 {Using the fact that the e4
pawn is not really hanging, as the a5 knight is hanging.} *

