1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 {Controlling the central e5-square and preparing Nf6!} 3. d4
{Going for the Open Sicilian.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {Developing the knight, made
possible by our pawn on d6.} 5. Nc3 a6 {This move defines the Najdorf. Now we
want to push e5 and Bb5+ is no longer an issue.} 6. Bc4 {6.Bc4 in the Najdorf
is a dangerous weapon that Fischer used to employ and it remains popular at
the amateur and club level. Contrary to the Fischer-Sozin Attack in the
Classical Sicilian where the knight is already on c6 and the pawn is still on
a7, Black has a lot more flexibility in his queenside development. This
variation is not seen too much at the high level anymore, but Black should
know his move orders not to get into trouble. White's bishop is aimed at the
e6 pawn, which is good on one hand, but on the other, as long as the e6 pawn
is well defended, the bishop could end up being a bad piece.} e6 {Here White
has a lot of different plans. First of all, there are a few ways of dealing
with the c4 bishop situation. White can play simply 7.Bb3 or try 7.a4 or 7.a3
ideas to drop the bishop to a2. White also has a big choice in terms of what
to do with his king. The old main-line is to castle short and develop with Qf3,
while in the latest high-level games White would more often try to go for
English Attack type ideas with Be3 Qe2/Qd2 and O-O-O.} 7. Bb3 b5 {Not 7...Be7
which would be a very natural mix up, because of 8.g4! After 7...b5 White has
a choice, whether to castle short or prepare the long castle, while 8.g4?! can
be met with 8...b4!} 8. Bg5 {Leads to some complications that Black should
know about, but objectively it doesn't seem to be too great for White. In any
case, the idea is to go Qf3 and castle long.} Be7 9. Qf3 Qc7 10. e5 {A
concrete try. Alternatively, White can go for the immediate long castle.} Bb7
11. exd6 {White opens up files.} Bxd6 12. Qe3 {Clearly, something will be
sacrificed on e6...} Bc5 13. O-O-O Nc6 {Now the 14.Nxe6 sacrifice doesn't work
because 14...Bxe3+ would be an intermediate check. Instead White has two ways
of playing this, in particular, the queen sacrifice that Ivanchuk once
unleashed is very pretty. Now that the surprise value is gone though, it is no
longer so dangerous.} 14. Qxe6+ {This is a very beautiful idea, White
sacrifices the queen for just two pawns. Upon recovering from the shock, Black
should realize that things aren't that bad.} fxe6 15. Nxe6 Qe7 16. Rhe1 Qxe6 {
A good thing about having an extra queen for two pawns is that you can give up
your own for just one light piece and still be up in material.} 17. Rxe6+ Ne7 {
White can win back the third pawn, but Black has nothing to worry about.} 18.
Rde1 O-O-O {Now White has to show some accuracy to hold balance here.} 19. Bxf6
gxf6 20. Ne4 {Getting rid of a very strong bishop.} Bxe4 21. R1xe4 f5 22. R4e5
Bd6 23. Rxe7 Bxe5 24. Rxe5 Rhe8 {Led to three draws in correspondence chess,
the highest rated one of them being Percze @@StartBracket@@2549@@EndBracket@@
- Krivic @@StartBracket@@2522@@EndBracket@@ all the way back in 2008.} *

