1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 {Controlling the central e5-square and preparing Nf6!} 3. d4
{Going for the Open Sicilian.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {Developing the knight, made
possible by our pawn on d6.} 5. Nc3 a6 {This move defines the Najdorf. Now we
want to push e5 and Bb5+ is no longer an issue.} 6. a4 {This is a very
positional system, that is really not very ambitious, yet very solid for White.
He shows that he doesn't intend to castle long in this game, making both the
Scheveningen setups with 6...e6 and the Dragon with 6...g6 more attractive.
Yet, he wants to restrain our queenside play and get a decent version of 6.Be2
e5 7.Nf3/6.Be3 e5 7.Nf3 lines. I still think 6...e5 is perfectly fine here and
I stay true to the philosophy of this course: whenever I can recommend 6...e5
I will recommend it. We have to rely on this pawn structure in the Najdorf.
Needless to say, if you are into Scheveningen or the Dragon structures, 6. a4
is probably one of the best lines to do so against.} e5 7. Nf3 {White's idea
is that he has not 'lost' any time with his bishops and now wants to develop
with Bc4 and Bg5 in one go. Makes sense, but of course, there are nuances here
too.} Be7 {Now White is mainly choosing between 8.Bc4 and 8.Bg5 . Developing
with 8.Be2 or 8.Be3 is less to the point, as White should be trying to
establish control over the d5 square. It is also possible to do some clever
stuff like 7...h6 , avoiding 8.Bg5 , but I like the simple approach to develop
quickly.} 8. Bc4 {This is very similar to the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/
p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.Be3 e5 7.Nf3
positions. Again we should play 8...Be6 but be aware of the important nuance,
not to blunder into Bxe6 fxe6 Ng5 by developing with Nbd7 and O-O.} Be6 {We
can also castle first, it mostly doesn't matter, but I like clarifying things
first. Now White has a few options 9.Bb3 , 9.Ba2 and 9.Qe2 , the differences
are not too big, but in all cases, mainly we just have to be careful about
Bxe6 Ng5 and develop accurately.} 9. Bb3 {There is no ideal square for this
bishop. Here it can also be a target for our knight.} Nbd7 {Intending to put
pressure on the b3 bishop with Nc5.} 10. Be3 Rc8 {Reinstating the Nc5 plans.}
11. O-O Nc5 {Grabbing one of the bishops is only half the job. We have to make
sure that White doesn't get to reroute his f3 knight towards the d5 square.}
12. Bxc5 Rxc5 13. Ne1 {White is heading towards the d5 square. Now it is very
important to prevent that, else White will have a very easy play.} Rc8 {Moving
out of the way, also possible to c6, there isn't much difference.} 14. Nd3 Qa5
{This is very important, controlling the b4 square and stopping the Nb4-Nd5
manoeuvre. Now White's concept fails and we have a comfortable position. We
want to castle and then have an idea of our own, such as the Bd8-Bb6 manoeuvre.
} *

[Event "?"]
