[Black "Open Sicilian - 6. Bd3 #1"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "36"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 {Controlling the central e5-square and preparing Nf6!} 3. d4
{Going for the Open Sicilian.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {Developing the knight, made
possible by our pawn on d6.} 5. Nc3 a6 {This move defines the Najdorf. Now we
want to push e5 and Bb5+ is no longer an issue.} 6. Bd3 {This is a very old
system that has not really been a thing for a long time until it became very
popular at the highest level a few years ago when White discovered some new
ideas here and there. I still don't expect you to come across it all too often,
but who knows your opponent's favourite player and/or streamer may have
successfully employed a bunch of times and he may want to try it out too!
Jokes aside, Hikaru Nakamura has been very successful with it, but also other
top players have tried it. The idea is to develop the bishop to d3 and keep
the e2 square free for the knight. The dragon setups used to be very popular
here, with 6...g6 and it still remains one of the main ways of playing, but at
some point, White had discovered that he can still go for the f3 Be3 Qd2 O-O-O
plan, which turned out to be quite poisonous. That is why I once tried 6...
Nbd7!? first and only after 7.O-O did I go 7...g6!? Anyway, all these are
playable, but I stay true to my philosophy in this course, of recommending the
e5 structure whenever possible.} e5 {This remains the main move here.} 7. Nde2
{This is the point of the system. Of course White can play 7.Nf3 or 7.Nb3 ,
but then he just has a strange version of the 6. Be2 e5 lines, as the bishop
on d3 is not any better placed than on e2. Black's play there is standard, we
go Be7 O-O and then develop our queenside with Be6 Nbd7 Rc8 and so on. That's
the good thing about this pawn structure, no matter what weird moves White
throws at us, we have our familiar harmonious development scheme.} Be7 {There
already are alternatives here, with Black coming up with subtle ideas like 7...
Nc6!? or 7...Be6!? in order to be very subtle. Definitely possible to look
into it, but I will try to keep things simple here.} 8. O-O O-O {Here too,
there is definitely a point in starting with 8...Be6 . The idea is to meet 9.
Ng3 with 9...Nc6 and then there is no 10.Nd5 jump because after 10...Nxd5 11.
exd5 Bxd5 there is no Bxh7+. The bishop on e6, however, is exposed to the f4
push, so there are some downsides there as well. I will show both options in
the main course, but we'll stick to 8...O-O in this Short & Sweet.} 9. Ng3 {
The main move, but there are also alternatives. Pushing f4 when the bishop is
not on e6 is @@StartBracket@@as usual@@EndBracket@@ somewhat premature, but a
waiting move like 9.h3!? makes sense.} Be6 {The most natural and healthy move,
but it does allow the 10. Nd5 resource. Black players also tried being clever
here and I once tried 9...Bg4!? here against Sergey Karjakin, trying to
confuse White's pieces before going back to e6, while Alireza Firouzja tried 9.
..Re8 here, which is a semi-waiting move, also against Karjakin and went on to
win a nice game. These two options deserve further investigation, but I will
stick to the main-line here.} 10. Nd5 {The only really critical continuation.
If White makes an empty move, we will happily develop with Nbd7 or even Nc6.}
Bxd5 {This is the main move and leads to one of the typical double-edged
Najdorf structures. Alternatively, I discovered that Black can also 'fall' for
it and capture on d5 twice.} 11. exd5 g6 {Stopping Nf5 first and intending to
follow up with the development of the b8 knight with Nbd7.} 12. c4 {The
main-move, reinforcing the d5 pawn and trying to get the majority going. White
can also include 12.Bh6 Re8 , it will transpose to 12. c4 anyway after 13.c4
Nbd7} Nbd7 {Finishing the development. This is a fascinating tabia, similar to
some variations of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/
R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/
p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.Be3 e5 7.Nb3
systems, with the nuance, that the knight which is usually badly placed on b3
is now placed less badly on g3. This gives White a lot easier play than in the
aforementioned systems, but it seems Black still has enough counterplay here
and I like the dark-squared potential we have here. Unlike the systems with
the knight on b3, I don't think the plans related to Ne8 Bg5 and f5 are
working all too well. After Ne8 White plays Bh6 Ng7 Qd2 and f5 is met with f3
when f4 gives up the e4 square for the g3 knight. At the same time, White will
get to push the queenside quite quickly with b4. Instead, what Black usually
aims for in this particular position is the b5!? counterplay, opening the
files on the queenside and undermining the d5 pawn. And that makes sense, as
because the White knight is not on b3 and thus not close to the c6 square, the
plan of b7-b5 is particularly justified here.} 13. a3 {Is a clever move that
Hikaru played against Nepo in a blitz game. Ian responded terribly with 13...
Nc5? 14.Bc2 b5 15.b4! when it transpired that 15...Ncd7 black will lose to 16.
c5! 13...Rb8 is also less attractive here due to 14.b4 , but I propose to go
for another idea altogether.} h5 {Intending to push the knight away with h4.}
14. Kh1 {Intending f4.} h4 15. Ne2 e4 {It's also possible to play slower, but
this works well, so why not.} 16. Bb1 {The other retreat 16.Bc2 is similar.}
Rc8 {Getting an extra move in, before pushing b5.} 17. b3 b5 18. cxb5 axb5 {
With a very complex position, but the d5 pawn is weak, White's pieces aren't
too active and we may want to regroup with Re8 Bf8-Bg7 making sure the king is
very safe.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Short & Sweet"]
[Black "Open Sicilian - 6. Bd3 #2"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "46"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 {Controlling the central e5-square and preparing Nf6!} 3. d4
{Going for the Open Sicilian.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {Developing the knight, made
possible by our pawn on d6.} 5. Nc3 a6 {This move defines the Najdorf. Now we
want to push e5 and Bb5+ is no longer an issue.} 6. Bd3 {This is a very old
system that has not really been a thing for a long time until it became very
popular at the highest level a few years ago when White discovered some new
ideas here and there. I still don't expect you to come across it all too often,
but who knows your opponent's favourite player and/or streamer may have
successfully employed a bunch of times and he may want to try it out too!
Jokes aside, Hikaru Nakamura has been very successful with it, but also other
top players have tried it. The idea is to develop the bishop to d3 and keep
the e2 square free for the knight. The dragon setups used to be very popular
here, with 6...g6 and it still remains one of the main ways of playing, but at
some point, White had discovered that he can still go for the f3 Be3 Qd2 O-O-O
plan, which turned out to be quite poisonous. That is why I once tried 6...
Nbd7!? first and only after 7.O-O did I go 7...g6!? Anyway, all these are
playable, but I stay true to my philosophy in this course, of recommending the
e5 structure whenever possible.} e5 {This remains the main move here.} 7. Nde2
{This is the point of the system. Of course White can play 7.Nf3 or 7.Nb3 ,
but then he just has a strange version of the 6. Be2 e5 lines, as the bishop
on d3 is not any better placed than on e2. Black's play there is standard, we
go Be7 O-O and then develop our queenside with Be6 Nbd7 Rc8 and so on. That's
the good thing about this pawn structure, no matter what weird moves White
throws at us, we have our familiar harmonious development scheme.} Be7 {There
already are alternatives here, with Black coming up with subtle ideas like 7...
Nc6!? or 7...Be6!? in order to be very subtle. Definitely possible to look
into it, but I will try to keep things simple here.} 8. O-O O-O {Here too,
there is definitely a point in starting with 8...Be6 . The idea is to meet 9.
Ng3 with 9...Nc6 and then there is no 10.Nd5 jump because after 10...Nxd5 11.
exd5 Bxd5 there is no Bxh7+. The bishop on e6, however, is exposed to the f4
push, so there are some downsides there as well. I will show both options in
the main course, but we'll stick to 8...O-O in this Short & Sweet.} 9. Ng3 {
The main move, but there are also alternatives. Pushing f4 when the bishop is
not on e6 is @@StartBracket@@as usual@@EndBracket@@ somewhat premature, but a
waiting move like 9.h3!? makes sense.} Be6 {The most natural and healthy move,
but it does allow the 10.Nd5 resource. Black players also tried being clever
here and I once tried 9...Bg4!? here against Sergey Karjakin, trying to
confuse White's pieces before going back to e6, while Alireza Firouzja tried 9.
..Re8 here, which is a semi-waiting move, also against Karjakin and went on to
win a nice game. These two options deserve further investigation, but I will
stick to the main-line here.} 10. Nd5 {The only really critical continuation.
If White makes an empty move, we will happily develop with Nbd7 or even Nc6.}
Bxd5 {This is the main move and leads to one of the typical double-edged
Najdorf structures. Alternatively, I discovered that Black can also 'fall' for
it and capture on d5 twice.} 11. exd5 g6 {Stopping Nf5 first and intending to
follow up with the development of the b8 knight with Nbd7.} 12. c4 {The
main-move, reinforcing the d5 pawn and trying to get the majority going. White
can also include 12.Bh6 Re8 , it will transpose to 12.c4 anyway after 13.c4
Nbd7} Nbd7 {Finishing the development. This is a fascinating tabia, similar to
some variations of the @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/
R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.Be2 e5 7.Nb3 or @@StartFEN@@rnbqkb1r/1p2pppp/
p2p1n2/8/3NP3/2N5/PPP2PPP/R1BQKB1R w KQkq - 0 6@@EndFEN@@ 6.Be3 e5 7.Nb3
systems, with the nuance, that the knight which is usually badly placed on b3
is now placed less badly on g3. This gives White a lot easier play than in the
aforementioned systems, but it seems Black still has enough counterplay here
and I like the dark-squared potential we have here. Unlike the systems with
the knight on b3, I don't think the plans related to Ne8 Bg5 and f5 are
working all too well. After Ne8 White plays Bh6 Ng7 Qd2 and f5 is met with f3
when f4 gives up the e4 square for the g3 knight. At the same time, White will
get to push the queenside quite quickly with b4. Instead, what Black usually
aims for in this particular position is the b5!? counterplay, opening the
files on the queenside and undermining the d5 pawn. And that makes sense, as
because the White knight is not on b3 and thus not close to the c6 square, the
plan of b7-b5 is particularly justified here.} 13. Bh6 {The most often played
move so far, but by no means necessary or best.} Re8 {I am not sure Black
minds to get this move for free and also we may now win a tempo on the h6
bishop with Bf8 next.} 14. Rc1 {This has been played in 5 games. White wants
to get ready for Black's queenside play and meet 14...Bf8 with 15.Bg5 h6 16.
Be3 or Bd2 16...e4 17.Bb1! when the rook on c1 and the bishop on b1 are
ideally placed to meet the b5 break in the end of this line. Still, at the end
of the line, we can play b5 and having done some analysis on this too, it
seems to me that Black can play this way as well.} Nc5 {The solution that
Wojtaszek showed against Nepo in FIDE GP Moscow 2019. The variation mentioned
with 14...Bf8 is also interesting, but this is more direct, Black wants to
kick away White's bishop and prepare b5 push later.} 15. Bb1 a5 {We want Nfd7
Bg5, but we also have Rb8-b5 idea if necessary.} 16. b3 {Intending a3-b4.} Rb8
{White's idea of a3 can now be met by b5!.} 17. f4 {So far following Nepo -
Wojtaszek. I repeat myself, but again, opening the f-file comes at a cost.
White weakens his dark squares and we get the knight on e5 potentially.} Bf8 {
Is also complex, though it might be easier.} 18. Bg5 exf4 {Otherwise, f5 was a
threat already when we wouldn't have our e5 square.} 19. Rxf4 Ncd7 {We need to
go all out to defend the f6 knight.} 20. Qf3 Bg7 21. Rf1 {Now it seems as
though we collapse under the tremendous pressure along the f-file, but it is
not the case.} Qb6+ 22. Kh1 Ne5 {And we get to regroup.} 23. Qd1 Nfd7 {The
position remains complex, but Black is fine here. Next, we want to start
counterplay with a4! White has the spectacular 24.Nh5 but it is only enough
for a draw after 24...gxh5 25.Qxh5 Nf8 26.Rxf7 Nxf7 27.Qxf7 Kh8 28.Bf6 Bxf6 29.
Qxf6+ with a perpetual on the f6-f7 squares. Also the simple 24...Bh8 is there.
} *

