[White "Short & Sweet"]
[Black "Open Sicilian - 6. f4"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "26"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 {Controlling the central e5-square and preparing Nf6!} 3. d4
{Going for the Open Sicilian.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {Developing the knight, made
possible by our pawn on d6.} 5. Nc3 a6 {This move defines the Najdorf. Now we
want to push e5 and Bb5+ is no longer an issue.} 6. f4 {This variation is not
all too popular at the top level, but it nevertheless has a small loyal fan
base. Usually, at least from my practice during my early career, those who
would play this line, would play this line a lot. It is though not too
poisonous. White determines the pawn structure very early, we will strike with
6...e5 and since you already studied the 6.Be2 variations, you know that as
long as Black's bishop is not on e6, the pawn on f4 has a rather vague purpose,
as the f5 push will always be met with a quick counterplay against the weak e4
pawn.} e5 7. Nb3 Nc6 {The natural 7...Be7 is fine, but there is an endgame
with 8.fxe5 that we have to deal with. This move avoids that endgame, while
still aiming to go for the Be7 O-O development.} 8. f5 {This push feels
overambitious when done without hitting the e6 bishop. Black has a few ways to
tackle it.} Be7 {It is also possible to start complications with immediate 8...
d5!? , but this move is also fine, first developing the bishop and waiting
with d5 or b5 counterplay for now.} 9. Bg5 {Falls into a nice tactic.} Nxe4 {
This works wonderfully here. By the way, this is a typical tactic for many
different openings as the combination of pieces pawn e4 Bg5 Nc3 Qd1 vs Nf6 Be7
Qd8 is very common.} 10. Nxe4 Bxg5 11. Nxd6+ {White wins back the pawn, but he
can never win back that dark square control.} Ke7 {Hitting the knight. The
king is just fine in the center for now @@StartBracket@@all the other 3 legal
moves favour White@@EndBracket@@.} 12. Qh5 {White has to get rid of our
dark-squared bishop.} Qxd6 13. Qxg5+ Qf6 {And White appears to be doing poorly,
as his f5 pawn is rather weak.} *

