[White "Short & Sweet"]
[Black "Open Sicilian - 6. Nb3"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "40"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 {Controlling the central e5-square and preparing Nf6!} 3. d4
{Going for the Open Sicilian.} cxd4 4. Nxd4 Nf6 {Developing the knight, made
possible by our pawn on d6.} 5. Nc3 a6 {This move defines the Najdorf. Now we
want to push e5 and Bb5+ is no longer an issue.} 6. Nb3 {This is a very
creative system, White is bracing for 6...e5 , while for 6...e6 he is ready to
lash out the direct 7.g4 While 6...e5 is indeed very bad, the other option 6...
e6 is something I can definitely recommend, as in the arising sharp positions
the knight on b3 is simply a lot more passive than it was on d4.} e6 {Instead,
6...e5 would be falling for it, as White would then go 7.Bg5 and get a good
version of the 6.Be2 line, without having to go Be2, so if you are looking for
an alternative, I would consider the flexible Nc6/Nbd7 type of moves.} 7. g4 {
This is White's idea. He gets to push the pawns on the kingside here, but the
knight on b3 is too passive for this setup to be really dangerous.} b5 {We
start our own expansion. Now White has been choosing from three options.} 8. a3
{It is also possible to make this move and not determine the f1 bishop to g2
yet.} Bb7 {Now I propose to go for Bb7, and invite White's bishop to g2 after
all.} 9. Bg2 Nfd7 {We need this move anyway, as White will probably push g5
sooner or later.} 10. g5 Nc6 {This is the square for the knight in this
variation, now that White's d4 knight has left to b3.} 11. h4 {White usually
pushes the h-pawn as well, at some point. If White castles short early, he
will have to also reckon with g6-h6 ideas.} Be7 {Finishing our development.
The direct 11...Nb6 also seems interesting.} 12. f4 {The most natural, pushing
all the pawns forward.} Nb6 {With the option of sending the knight to c4, to
prevent White from developing with Be3 Qe2 and O-O-O.} 13. f5 O-O {I prefer to
castle first, but also interesting are 13...Nc4 and 13...Na4!?} 14. Qg4 {
Principled, threatening not just fxe6, but mainly f6.} exf5 {The most direct
attempt at clarifying things.} 15. exf5 Re8 {We need to move the rook from f8
sooner or later, as f6 remained a threat.} 16. O-O Ne5 {Trading White's
powerful light-squared bishop.} 17. Qh3 Bxg2 18. Qxg2 d5 {Gaining more space
in the center. In such positions, White's kingside pawns are just as weakening
as they are threatening.} 19. f6 Bd6 {We can just move out of the way.} 20.
fxg7 Rc8 {We let the g7 pawn guard our king and next we want to swing our c8
rook over via c4.21.Nd4 eying for f5 can be met with 21...Bc5!} *

[Event "?"]
