[White "Short & Sweet"]
[Black "4. Qxd4 & 5. f3"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "36"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 {Controlling the central e5-square and preparing Nf6!} 3. d4
{Going for the Open Sicilian.} cxd4 4. Qxd4 {This system used to be played
mainly with the idea to pin the knight on c6 and then take it, develop with
Nc3 Bg5 and castle long. Nowadays, some top players started playing it with
different ideas, like dropping the queen back to e3 and simply finishing the
development. It is not that dangerous, in particular for players who aren't
that experienced and want to improve their game, I would recommend, as White,
to stay away from such slightly disharmonious systems. That said, as Najdorf
players, we are always happy to face these systems, so let's see how to react.}
Nc6 {I had played the 4...Nf6 move order against Carlsen and there are some
subtle points there, but it is a lot easier to go for 4...Nc6 , with more
clarity and much fewer transpositions. Now White is choosing from 2 different
concepts, the traditional 5.Bb5 and the rare 5.Qe3 which is a very odd-looking
setup that has been played a lot at the highest level recently.} 5. Bb5 {The
old way of doing it, White pins the knight and doesn't want to waste time
moving the queen again. I expect this still to be the most common of the two
on amateur and club level, despite that a lot of top players are trying these
hypermodern Qe3 setups.} Bd7 {Here again White has a choice. The traditional
way to go is to grab the knight and go for the quick long castle with Nc3 Bg5,
while the more modern attempts are connected with the Maroczy bind.} 6. Bxc6
Bxc6 7. Nc3 {This is the old setup, the computers have long shown that this
highly ambitious setup is not near as dangerous as it looks.} Nf6 {We may want
to fianchetto the bishop, so White stops that.} 8. Bg5 {Forcing us to go for
the e6 Be7 setup, which is fine.} e6 9. O-O-O Be7 {Now White usually tries
something like Qd3 Nd4 and then starts pushing the kingside pawns. Pretty slow.
} 10. Rhe1 {The most often played move. There are really a lot of games in the
database here.} O-O {We should castle and now White has a lot of choice and a
lot of games in this position. It is an ancient tabia that modern computers
are laughing at- Black is completely fine as we will see.} 11. e5 {This direct
attempt has been tried over 500 times, but it really doesn't lead anywhere.}
dxe5 12. Qh4 {This is how they mostly play.} Qc7 13. Nxe5 {White intends Ng4
and has some illusion of pressure here.} Rfd8 {A natural move, intending some
trades. The threat of Ng4 is not real. For the record, the more complex 13...
h6!? also seems to lead to a good position.} 14. Ng4 {Looks intimidating, but
we have a strong sequence here.} Rxd1+ 15. Rxd1 Nxg4 {We take.} 16. Bxe7 {And
here the very important resource} Nh6 {and with Nf5 incoming, it is Black who
claims a small advantage here.} 17. Bd6 Nf5 18. Bxc7 Nxh4 {The endgame is
slightly better for Black, as we have clearly better pieces after 19.g3 Nf3 .}
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
