[White "Short & Sweet"]
[Black "3. Bb5+"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "24"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 {Controlling the central e5-square and preparing Nf6!} 3.
Bb5+ {This used to be a safe sideline for White, that has always been around
at club and amateur level. Who doesn't like to give a check and castle as fast
as possible? But it wasn't until around a decade ago when it was picked up by
the leading players, including Magnus Carlsen, that it suddenly became one of
the most testing systems against the Najdorf. At first, it brought Black
players a lot of problems, but by now slowly the solutions started
crystallizing and the Najdorf fans have found various ways to deal with it.}
Nd7 {I am going to recommend 3...Nd7 . To be honest, I think 3...Bd7 is a lot
easier and would also take up a lot less space on the course, but I feel that
it would be unfair to those who play Najdorf as a fighting weapon and want to
get as complicated positions as possible. 3...Nd7 is more in the spirit! After
3...Bd7 the main-line is 4.Bxd7 when Black again has a choice, 4...Qxd7 is the
old main-line when White has two plans the one with c3-d4 5.O-O Nf6 6.Re1 Nc6
7.c3 e6 8.d4 And the more critical c4 aiming for the Maroczy bind 5.c4 Nf6 6.
Nc3 g6 7.d4 etc. By now Black had figured out various ways of equalizing
against it, I would recommend those interested to study the latest games at
the highest level. Another option is 4...Nxd7!? which had become very popular
at the high level recently. There too, White can either go for the center with
the c3-d4 idea or try for a Maroczy bind of sorts. And again, according to the
latest high-level games Black holds his own. I for one used the 3...Bd7 4.Bxd7
Nxd7 line twice in a very important blitz tournament and scored 1½ out of 2
by drawing Magnus Carlsen and beating Maxime Vachier Lagrave with it. Back to
3...Nd7 , White now has a lot of different options.} 4. O-O {The immediate
short castle is very natural and is obviously one of the critical moves.} a6 {
Starting with 4...Ngf6 is also possible, but then we have to deal with 5.Re1
a6 6.Bf1!? extra option.} 5. Bd3 {This was really very fashionable for a while.
White is aiming to get a strong center with c3 Bc2 and d4 and it took Black
quite a while to come up with good ways to challenge that plan.} Ngf6 6. Re1 {
This is a slightly clever move order, the idea being that if now Black goes 6..
.b5 White gets 7.c4!? in one go.} e6 {Those who want more murky play and care
less about reaching objectively equality out of the opening, I definitely
recommend you to look for alternatives here. For example 6...g6!? is worth
some self-study.} 7. a4 {Has also been played at the high level in quite a few
games. White's idea is to stop b5 and delay c3 for now.} b6 {We should develop
the bishop after all.} 8. c3 Bb7 9. Qe2 {This move is very logical and has
been played a few times by strong players @@StartBracket@@twice by
Svidler!@@EndBracket@@, but here I have a novelty ready for a very long time
and I am surprised it still hasn't been played, as by now the computer shows
it right away.} g5 {Using the fact that White has delayed his queenside
development far too long and the knight on f3 does not have that many squares.
White is already in serious trouble.} 10. Nxg5 {Capturing the pawn is going to
end badly for White.} Rg8 11. Nf3 d5 {Hitting in the center and using the full
power of the b7 bishop.} 12. e5 Nh5 {Now we see why 9. Qe2 was so bad. The
queen is in the way of Nf4 now and White is just lost.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Short & Sweet"]
[Black "3. Nc3"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "30"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nf3 d6 {Besides the open Sicilian 3.d4 , White also very often
delivers the 3.Bb5+ which has become particularly popular a few years back
when the top players, including Magnus Carlsen, had discovered that it can
even be used as an attempt to fight for an advantage. However, there are also
other 3rd moves and although they are a lot less trendy, some are still quite
common across all levels and as the character of the position is very
different compared to the open Sicilians, I believe it is worth your time to
go through these lines to get a better feel for them.} 3. Nc3 {With this move,
White doesn't 'burn the bridges' and can still go back into the open-Sicilian,
but he also has a couple of extra options that we should have a look at.} Nf6 {
Alternatives are 3...a6!? trying to transpose to our Najdorf and avoid the 3...
Nf6 4.e5 line or 3...e5!? which is very principled, not allowing White to go
back into the open Sicilian.} 4. h3 {The idea of this move is not entirely
clear, White is sort of waiting for Black to play Nc6 before going d4,
avoiding the Najdorf, but we don't have to obsess over Najdorf and can play a
good version of the Classical Sicilian.} Nc6 {It is also possible to play 4...
a6 and hope for a transposition and also the dragon with 4...g6!? here is a
pretty decent one, with White having played h2-h3. That said, I think this is
the simplest.} 5. d4 {Waiting further would be hard.} cxd4 6. Nxd4 e5 {The
positions will be similar to our Najdorf here. The structure is identical.} 7.
Nxc6 {Is a strategically risky line that Hikaru used against me in a blitz
game once.} bxc6 8. Bc4 Be7 9. O-O O-O 10. Qe2 {There are different options
here, but I sent the knight to b6, which I think was reasonable. Also possible
is to offer a trade of bishops with 10...Be6 .} Nd7 11. Rd1 Nb6 12. Bb3 a5 {
Hinting at a4 ideas.} 13. Be3 {I think safer for White was to trade the
knights with 13.Na4 , but Hikaru plays for complications here.} Ba6 {For now
13...a4 is met with 14.Bxb6!} 14. Qg4 {Hikaru went for the most active move.}
Kh8 {Stepping out just in case, and hinting at f5 push.} 15. f4 {A blunder!} a4
{And suddenly White lost a piece, as taking on a4 is met with Bc8, while
taking on b6 is no longer possible, because of the check, now that the pawn is
on f4. I managed to even lose this blitz game somehow, but at this point,
Black is just winning.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Short & Sweet"]
[Black "Grand Prix Attack (2. Nc3 d6 "]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "40"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 d6 3. f4 {The so-called Grand-Prix Attack. A beautiful opening,
White wants to develop with Nf3 Bc4 O-O, throw the f4 pawn forward and
checkmate us with the Qe1-Qh4 d3 Bh6 idea. This works in the fantasy world,
but if Black knows what he is doing, it can backfire on White.} g6 {No need to
fear d4, although Nc6 first is also possible. In that case though, 3...Nc6 can
be met with 4.Bb5} 4. Nf3 Bg7 {Now White is choosing mostly between the
standard 5.Bc4 and a more subtle 5.Bb5+ first.} 5. Bb5+ Bd7 6. Bc4 {This is
very subtle. The point is that in many of the complications after the eventual
f4-f5 pawn sac, the d6 pawn will be hanging when White will attack it, with
Qg3, or Bf4 or even Nb5. Very clever and Black has to know what he is doing
and not get confused.} Nc6 7. d3 {This is a clever idea, postponing O-O one
move.} e6 8. f5 {Pushing this without including 8.O-O Nge7 changes the dynamic
quite a bit. There after 9.f5 we could just castle, but here if we ignore 8.f5
and go Nge7? we get hit by 9.Ng5!} gxf5 {Not the only way, but I like the
forced nature of it.} 9. exf5 {This allows us to grab the center, but being
behind in development, things are not so easy for Black either.} d5 10. Bb5
Nge7 {Completing the development.} 11. Bxc6 Bxc6 {There are options, but I
like this line.} 12. fxe6 fxe6 13. Qe2 O-O {It is possible to hang on to the
pawn with 13...Qd6 with a mess, but I like this forced solution, taking care
of the king safety first.} 14. Qxe6+ Kh8 15. Bg5 {Critical.} d4 {Also possible
is 15...Qc7 , but this is once again the most forcing.} 16. Ne4 Qd5 17. Qxe7 {
Taking the piece is very dangerous:} Rae8 18. Qc7 Rxe4+ {Breaking through with
this exchange @@StartBracket@@in fact a rook!@@EndBracket@@ sacrifice.} 19.
dxe4 Qxe4+ 20. Kd2 d3 {And White has to defend with only moves here as Qb4 is
coming.} *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Short & Sweet"]
[Black "Alapin (2. c3)"]
[Result "*"]
[PlyCount "34"]

1. e4 c5 2. c3 {The Alapin is a relatively popular sideline which is
considered to be an easy and a safe way for White to handle all of the
Sicilians at once. I must admit, it is indeed very solid and relatively easy
for White to learn, but at the same time, it is really very harmless. While
White is aiming to build a strong pawn center with 3.d4, in reality, it is
quite the opposite. With Black to move here, we get the crucial tempo to
challenge White's control of the center. Note, that against Najdorf players
White can only play Alapin on the second move. Against those who play 2.Nf3 e6
or 2.Nf3 Nc6 Sicilian, White can start with 2.Nf3 and only then go 2...-- 3.c3
@@StartBracket@@which in fact avoids my recommendation against
Alapin!@@EndBracket@@. Against 2.Nf3 d6 however, 3.c3 Nf6 is a different story,
as 4.e5 is no longer the same because the e5 square is guarded by our d6 pawn.}
Nf6 {There are two main ways of handling the Alapin, the move I recommend and
2...d5 which is definitely good enough as well. The idea of 2...d5 is that
compared to the Scandinavian defence @@StartBracket@@1...d5@@EndBracket@@, the
c3 square is no longer available for the knight and so the queen on d5 is
feeling majestic. And yes, the Scandinavian is not a good opening.} 3. e5 Nd5 {
Here White has a choice from a couple of move orders. In general, there are
two main ways of treating this position with White. One is to go for a quick
d4 push and another one is to start with Bc4 challenging the d5 knight before
pushing the d-pawn. Sometimes these two inter-transpose. Meanwhile, Black's
idea is simple: we want to undermine the far advanced e-pawn with the d7-d6
break and will pretty much always meet Bc4 with a tempo-retreat Nb6.} 4. Nf3 d6
{This move is an attempt to avoid a major tabiya that arises after the main
move 4...Nc6 5.Bc4 Nb6 6.Bb3 The idea there is that after 6...d6 7.exd6 Qxd6
White has a lot of tricky ideas and can delay the d2-d4 push.} 5. d4 cxd4 6.
Qxd4 {I ran into trouble against this move in a blitz game once, so you should
know how to deal with it. If you do, it is not at all challenging.} e6 7. Nbd2
{This is the tricky move, waiting for Nc6 to pin it with Bb5 and then exert
pressure with Nc4.} Nc6 8. Bb5 {This is the tricky one.} Bd7 9. Bxc6 {White
doesn't waste time.} Bxc6 10. Nc4 {I remember the first time I faced this move
in a blitz game I was somewhat taken aback, but in fact there is a very
straightforward solution here.} b5 {Forcing the matters. It is quite important
to protect the c4 square for later.} 11. Nxd6+ Bxd6 12. exd6 O-O {Now Black
solved one important issue: we have castled our king to safety. The only
remaining issue is the d6 pawn, but we should be able to pick it up.} 13. b3 {
Preparing c4 looks clever, but we have a strong sequence here.} Qxd6 14. c4
bxc4 15. bxc4 e5 {Using the fact that the White king hasn't castled yet.} 16.
Qd2 Qg6 {Power play, hitting the g2 pawn.} 17. cxd5 Bb5 {This brilliant slow
move is the point. The White king is stuck in the center of the board and
despite being a piece up, he is the one who finds himself in a critical
position. Black can play this one slowly, the king will not run anywhere from
e1.} *

